<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>I use <code>nvm</code> to manage node versions. When I inspect <code>exec-path</code>, it contains a version of node that I no longer have installed, i.e. <code>~/.nvm/versions/node/v17.3.0/bin</code> is in my <code>exec-path</code>, but I only have the most recent stable and lts versions installed (v17.4 and v.16.3.2, respectively).</p> <p>So, two questions:</p> <p>1 - Naturally, how can I fix this? I&#39;ve tried using <code>(setenv NODE_PATH ...)</code>, but that didn&#39;t work. I tried <code>(setq exec-path (append exec-path (file-name-directory (shell-command-to-string &quot;which node&quot;))))</code> but that didn&#39;t do the trick either.</p> <p>2 - How might this have happened, so I can stop it from happening again in the future?</p> <p>Thanks very much.</p> </div><!-- SC_ON --> &#32; submitted by &#32; <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/bigpotatopieguy"> /u/bigpotatopieguy </a> <br/> <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/emacs/comments/sbwb7k/wrong_version_of_node_in_execpath/">[link]</a></span> &#32; <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/emacs/comments/sbwb7k/wrong_version_of_node_in_execpath/">[comments]</a></span>